text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%0a!AAVE and Hiring Policies%0a%0a:Author: BenP%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aThis article explores how the hiring process is affected by accent.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThis article:%0ahttps://acloserlookataave.wordpress.com/2014/03/05/58/%0a%0aand the associated video linked to it discuss how AAVE accents are viewed and discriminated against by employers looking to hire applicants. A linked expansion on the page details examples like the syllable deletion to go from "about" to "'bout", or the use of the Auxiliary contraction "ain't."%0a%0aIn the video, linguists and other experts explore the line between not hiring someone based on assumptions about the person's intelligence or education based solely on the AAVE accent, and not hiring someone because their accent makes them hard to understand. They delineate between the two by explaining how the first is based on nothing more than mere prejudice against speakers of AAVE or other accents and how the second is based on the practicality of hiring an employee that is incomprehensible due to their accent. In a sense, the difference lies in whether the accent or the preconceived notions about speakers of that accent are the reason someone is not hired. %0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210430-233136-495630#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Discrimination in classrooms %0a-> - khushiw%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aAs we discussed in class, many speakers of AAVE have to code switch in order to be perceived as professional when applying for jobs and interacting with others in the workplace. This is extremely unfair because people who are not Black take advantage of AAVE to earn social capital when Black people are discriminated against for using the same language. This article by the Harvard Business Review describes how students have to code switch as well, only they do it in classrooms. This is difficult because it impedes on one's learning to have to make a conscious switch while trying to pay attention and learn. This creates an unsafe environment for learning and makes it more difficult for Black students to learn at their maximum potential. %0a%0aSource: https://hbr.org/2019/11/the-costs-of-codeswitching%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210430-233136-495630#%0a#foxbegin 210501-181015-797560#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!AAVE housing discrimination %0a-> - TimG%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aThese examples of AAVE discrimination are not limited to the classroom or the job room. John Baugh, professor at Washington University in St. Louis, did a study on voice discrimination in applying to apartments, and found that if you were to respond to an ad with AAVE or hispanic English, you were far more likely to be rejected outright, not even being accepted to be considered for the apartment. This impacts even the ability to get housing for speakers of those dialects of English.%0a%0aThe article: %0ahttps://source.wustl.edu/2006/02/linguistic-profiling-the-sound-of-your-voice-may-determine-if-you-get-that-apartment-or-not/%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210501-181015-797560#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a#foxbegin 210501-054627-83240#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-30.04.2021 - 22:46-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210501-054627-83240 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a!!!!!Abi_S%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a'''prejudice vs. practicality'''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0alooked for an example of a job where it would be valid to select a person based on their accent, because I couldn't come up with any, but this article points out it would be valid for acting related jobs :https://theoutline.com/post/2224/these-linkedin-job-postings-requesting-a-neutral-accent-are-probably-illegal %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210501-054627-83240#%0a#foxbegin 210501-054522-652220#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-30.04.2021 - 22:45-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210501-054522-652220 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a!!!!!Abi_S%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a'''prejudice vs. practicality '''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0alooked for an example of a job where a "neutral" accent would be necessary (aka standardized American English)  %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210501-054522-652220#%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: E:)%0a(:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)
